        "content": "     1→[\n     2→  {\n     3→    \"title\": \"AI coding trends: 75% of enterprise teams to use AI IDEs by 2026\",\n     4→    \"description\": \"Industry analysis predicts 75% of enterprise development teams will use AI IDEs for full 'requirement-to-deployment' workflows by end of 2026. The global generative AI programming assistant market expected to reach $97.9 million by 2030. ByteDance's Trae, Cursor, and GLM-4.5 emerge as developer favorites.\",\n     5→    \"author\": \"Industry analysts\",\n     6→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n     7→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/a7611079469188727296/\",\n     8→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n     9→    \"topics\": [\n    10→      \"enterprise-adoption\",\n    11→      \"ai-ides\",\n    12→      \"market-predictions\",\n    13→      \"trae\",\n    14→      \"cursor\",\n    15→      \"glm\"\n    16→    ],\n    17→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    18→  },\n    19→  {\n    20→    \"title\": \"OpenClaw + Codex/ClaudeCode Agent Swarm: Single-person development teams\",\n    21→    \"description\": \"Technical guides emerged showing how to combine OpenClaw with Codex and ClaudeCode to create powerful agent swarms enabling single-person development teams. The integration allows autonomous coding, testing, and deployment with minimal human intervention.\",\n    22→    \"author\": \"Developer community\",\n    23→    \"source\": \"Technical\",\n    24→    \"url\": \"https://m.blog.csdn.net/riemann_/article/details/158394065\",\n    25→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n    26→    \"topics\": [\n    27→      \"openclaw\",\n    28→      \"codex\",\n    29→      \"claude-code\",\n    30→      \"agent-swarm\",\n    31→      \"automation\",\n    32→      \"productivity\"\n    33→    ],\n    34→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    35→  },\n    36→  {\n    37→    \"title\": \"OpenClaw founder Peter Steinberger joins OpenAI\",\n    38→    \"description\": \"Peter Steinberger, creator of OpenClaw (formerly Moltbot/Clawdbot), joined OpenAI to lead next-generation personal agent development. OpenClaw became the fastest-growing GitHub project in history with 175,000+ stars. The project will transition to an independent non-profit foundation funded by OpenAI, keeping the code open source.\",\n    39→    \"author\": \"OpenAI\",\n    40→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    41→    \"url\": \"https://k.sina.cn/article_7857201856_1d45362c001902m3ue.html\",\n    42→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-25\",\n    43→    \"topics\": [\n    44→      \"openai\",\n    45→      \"openclaw\",\n    46→      \"peter-steinberger\",\n    47→      \"ai-agents\",\n    48→      \"acquisitions\",\n    49→      \"open-source\"\n    50→    ],\n    51→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    52→  },\n    53→  {\n    54→    \"title\": \"Claude code surpasses Codex in Google Trends\",\n    55→    \"description\": \"Google Trends data from February 2026 shows Claude code-related searches surpassing Codex, signaling a shift in the AI programming tools market. This reflects Anthropic's growing influence in AI-assisted programming.\",\n    56→    \"author\": \"Market analysis\",\n    57→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    58→    \"url\": \"https://k.sina.cn/article/7879848900_1d5acf3c401902pnce.html\",\n    59→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    60→    \"topics\": [\n    61→      \"google-trends\",\n    62→      \"claude\",\n    63→      \"codex\",\n    64→      \"market-analysis\",\n    65→      \"anthropic\",\n    66→      \"openai\"\n    67→    ],\n    68→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    69→  },\n    70→  {\n    71→    \"title\": \"AI reasoning models learn when to 'stop thinking'\",\n    72→    \"description\": \"Beihang University, ByteDance, and Renmin University published arXiv:2602.08354v1, discovering that AI reasoning models can learn when to stop thinking. Accepted to ICML 2026, this addresses computational efficiency in reasoning models.\",\n    73→    \"author\": \"Beihang University, ByteDance, Renmin University\",\n    74→    \"source\": \"Paper\",\n    75→    \"url\": \"https://new.qq.com/rain/a/20260224A03C5200\",\n    76→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    77→    \"topics\": [\n    78→      \"arxiv\",\n    79→      \"reasoning\",\n    80→      \"icml-2026\",\n    81→      \"efficiency\",\n    82→      \"bytedance\",\n    83→      \"research\"\n    84→    ],\n    85→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    86→  },\n    87→  {\n    88→    \"title\": \"Seven mind-blowing truths about Vibe Coding revealed\",\n    89→    \"description\": \"Industry analysis revealed seven key insights about 'Vibe Coding' - the emerging paradigm where developers use natural language and AI assistants to build software. The article discusses how this differs from traditional programming and why it's controversial among professional developers.\",\n    90→    \"author\": \"Tech analysts\",\n    91→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    92→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/article/7606994594177450511/\",\n    93→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    94→    \"topics\": [\n    95→      \"vibe-coding\",\n    96→      \"ai-coding\",\n    97→      \"paradigm-shift\",\n    98→      \"controversy\",\n    99→      \"developer-tools\"\n   100→    ],\n   101→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   102→  },\n   103→  {\n   104→    \"title\": \"OpenClaw founder: Meta and OpenAI competed to acquire\",\n   105→    \"description\": \"Peter Steinberger revealed that both Meta (Mark Zuckerberg personally) and OpenAI (Sam Altman) attempted to acquire OpenClaw. Steinberger rejected both offers, insisting the project must remain open source. The story highlights the strategic value of open-source AI agent infrastructure.\",\n   106→    \"author\": \"Peter Steinberger (via Wall Street CN, 36Kr)\",\n   107→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   108→    \"url\": \"https://wallstreetcn.com/articles/3765726\",\n   109→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n   110→    \"topics\": [\n   111→      \"openclaw\",\n   112→      \"acquisitions\",\n   113→      \"meta\",\n   114→      \"openai\",\n   115→      \"open-source\",\n   116→      \"peter-steinberger\"\n   117→    ],\n   118→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   119→  },\n   120→  {\n   121→    \"title\": \"Ladybird adopts Rust, with help from AI\",\n   122→    \"description\": \"Andreas Kling shared a case study on sophisticated use of coding agents for ambitious projects. Ladybird switched from Swift to Rust, using Claude Code and Codex to port their LibJS JavaScript engine (25,000 lines of Rust in two weeks instead of months). Key insight: Having existing conformance testing suites (like test262) makes agentic engineering much safer, as you can compare output with trusted implementations.\",\n   123→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison (citing Andreas Kling)\",\n   124→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   125→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   126→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n   127→    \"topics\": [\n   128→      \"ai\",\n   129→      \"rust\",\n   130→      \"browsers\",\n   131→      \"coding-agents\",\n   132→      \"agentic-engineering\",\n   133→      \"test262\"\n   134→    ],\n   135→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   136→  },\n   137→  {\n   138→    \"title\": \"Writing about Agentic Engineering Patterns\",\n   139→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison launched a new project to document Agentic Engineering Patterns—coding practices and patterns for getting the best results from coding agent development. This reflects the growing maturity of AI-assisted programming as a discipline.\",\n   140→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   141→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   142→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   143→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n   144→    \"topics\": [\n   145→      \"agentic-engineering\",\n   146→      \"coding-agents\",\n   147→      \"design-patterns\",\n   148→      \"ai-assisted-programming\"\n   149→    ],\n   150→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   151→  },\n   152→  {\n   153→    \"title\": \"Writing code is cheap now\",\n   154→    \"description\": \"The biggest challenge in adopting agentic engineering is getting comfortable with the fact that writing code is now cheap. This fundamental shift challenges decades of engineering habits built around code being expensive. Planning and design remain crucial, but the cost of implementation has dropped dramatically.\",\n   155→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   156→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   157→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   158→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n   159→    \"topics\": [\n   160→      \"agentic-engineering\",\n   161→      \"economics-of-programming\",\n   162→      \"ai-assisted-programming\",\n   163→      \"coding-agents\"\n   164→    ],\n   165→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   166→  },\n   167→  {\n   168→    \"title\": \"Red/green TDD with coding agents\",\n   169→    \"description\": \"A key agentic engineering pattern: Use red/green TDD (Test Driven Development) to get better results from coding agents. Writing tests first and having the agent iterate until tests pass leads to more reliable outcomes.\",\n   170→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n   171→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   172→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   173→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-23\",\n   174→    \"topics\": [\n   175→      \"tdd\",\n   176→      \"testing\",\n   177→      \"ai-assisted-programming\",\n   178→      \"coding-agents\",\n   179→      \"agentic-engineering\"\n   180→    ],\n   181→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   182→  },\n   183→  {\n   184→    \"title\": \"OpenClaw and OpenCode combination guide\",\n   185→    \"description\": \"Developer guides showed how to combine OpenClaw with OpenCode for end-to-end automation from requirements to code. The combination enables autonomous requirement analysis, code generation, testing, and deployment with minimal human intervention.\",\n   186→    \"author\": \"Developer community\",\n   187→    \"source\": \"Technical\",\n   188→    \"url\": \"https://juejin.cn/post/7609660097766014986\",\n   189→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   190→    \"topics\": [\n   191→      \"openclaw\",\n   192→      \"opencode\",\n   193→      \"automation\",\n   194→      \"end-to-end\",\n   195→      \"integration\",\n   196→      \"tutorials\"\n   197→    ],\n   198→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   199→  },\n   200→  {\n   201→    \"title\": \"Programming as craft is dying, building as capability is exploding\",\n   202→    \"description\": \"OpenClaw founder Peter Steinberger's profound observation: 'Programming as a craft is dying, but building as a capability is exploding.' This captures the fundamental shift from manual coding to AI-orchestrated development, where developers become architects and reviewers rather than writers of code.\",\n   203→    \"author\": \"Peter Steinberger (via industry analysis)\",\n   204→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   205→    \"url\": \"https://m.sohu.com/a/987267072_453160/?pvid=000115_3w_a\",\n   206→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   207→    \"topics\": [\n   208→      \"openclaw\",\n   209→      \"paradigm-shift\",\n   210→      \"ai-coding\",\n   211→      \"developer-roles\",\n   212→      \"philosophy\"\n   213→    ],\n   214→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   215→  },\n   216→  {\n   217→    \"title\": \"GLM-5 open source: Best open-source model for Agentic Engineering era\",\n   218→    \"description\": \"Zhipu AI released GLM-5 as 'the best open-source model for Agentic Engineering', achieving 77.8 on SWE-bench-Verified (open-source SOTA) and 56.2 on Terminal Bench 2.0. With 744B parameters (40B active), it outperforms Gemini 3 Pro and is designed specifically for 'writing engineering, not just code'.\",\n   219→    \"author\": \"Zhipu AI\",\n   220→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   221→    \"url\": \"https://finance.sina.com.cn/tech/roll/2026-02-12/doc-inhmqmpz6669028.shtml\",\n   222→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   223→    \"topics\": [\n   224→      \"glm-5\",\n   225→      \"zhipu-ai\",\n   226→      \"agentic-engineering\",\n   227→      \"benchmarks\",\n   228→      \"chinese-ai\",\n   229→      \"open-source\"\n   230→    ],\n   231→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   232→  },\n   233→  {\n   234→    \"title\": \"The Claude C Compiler: What It Reveals About the Future of Software\",\n   235→    \"description\": \"Chris Lattner's review of Anthropic's Claude C Compiler (built with parallel Claudes). Key insights: Good software depends on judgment, communication, and clear abstraction—AI has amplified this. AI coding automates implementation, making design and stewardship more important. CCC looks like a competent textbook implementation but isn't production-ready yet.\",\n   236→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison (citing Chris Lattner)\",\n   237→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   238→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   239→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   240→    \"topics\": [\n   241→      \"compilers\",\n   242→      \"c\",\n   243→      \"anthropic\",\n   244→      \"claude\",\n   245→      \"coding-agents\",\n   246→      \"agentic-engineering\"\n   247→    ],\n   248→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   249→  },\n   250→  {\n   251→    \"title\": \"How I think about Codex\",\n   252→    \"description\": \"Gabriel Chua (OpenAI) explains that Codex = Model + Harness + Surfaces. Notably, Codex models are trained in the presence of the harness—tool use, execution loops, and iterative verification are part of how the model learns, not bolted-on behaviors.\",\n   253→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison (citing Gabriel Chua)\",\n   254→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   255→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   256→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   257→    \"topics\": [\n   258→      \"openai\",\n   259→      \"codex\",\n   260→      \"definitions\",\n   261→      \"llms\",\n   262→      \"ai-assisted-programming\"\n   263→    ],\n   264→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   265→  },\n   266→  {\n   267→    \"title\": \"OpenClaw deployment on Alibaba Cloud with Qwen integration\",\n   268→    \"description\": \"Alibaba Cloud released quick deployment guides and 'Coding Plan' packages optimized for OpenClaw, integrating with Qwen (Tongyi Qianwen) models for Chinese users. This marks the first major cloud provider to officially support OpenClaw deployment.\",\n   269→    \"author\": \"Alibaba Cloud\",\n   270→    \"source\": \"Technical\",\n   271→    \"url\": \"https://developer.aliyun.com/article/1713071\",\n   272→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-22\",\n   273→    \"topics\": [\n   274→      \"alibaba-cloud\",\n   275→      \"openclaw\",\n   276→      \"qwen\",\n   277→      \"deployment\",\n   278→      \"cloud-computing\",\n   279→      \"chinese-ai\"\n   280→    ],\n   281→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   282→  },\n   283→  {\n   284→    \"title\": \"Andrej Karpathy talks about 'Claws'\",\n   285→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy tweeted about buying a Mac Mini to tinker with Claws. He views Claws as a new layer on top of LLM agents, taking orchestration, scheduling, context, tool calls, and persistence to the next level. NanoClaw is highlighted as interesting (~4,000 lines of code, container-based). The term 'Claw' is becoming a category name for OpenClaw-like agent systems that run on personal hardware.\",\n   286→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison (citing Andrej Karpathy)\",\n   287→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n   288→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/\",\n   289→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   290→    \"topics\": [\n   291→      \"andrej-karpathy\",\n   292→      \"definitions\",\n   293→      \"ai-agents\",\n   294→      \"openclaw\",\n   295→      \"agentic-engineering\"\n   296→    ],\n   297→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   298→  },\n   299→  {\n   300→    \"title\": \"Karpathy's 'Falling Behind' tweet goes viral\",\n   301→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy tweeted that he has 'never felt so strongly behind' in keeping up with AI tools, stating that properly chaining AI tools can make developers '10x more powerful'. The tweet went viral with 10,000+ retweets, resonating across the developer community about the pace of AI advancement.\",\n   302→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n   303→    \"source\": \"Twitter\",\n   304→    \"url\": \"https://www.donews.com/news/detail/4/6407986.html\",\n   305→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   306→    \"topics\": [\n   307→      \"andrej-karpathy\",\n   308→      \"ai-tools\",\n   309→      \"developer-productivity\",\n   310→      \"viral\",\n   311→      \"industry-sentiment\"\n   312→    ],\n   313→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   314→  },\n   315→  {\n   316→    \"title\": \"Qwen 3.5 and Qwen Coder released\",\n   317→    \"description\": \"Alibaba's Qwen team released Qwen 3.5, a 397B Mixture-of-Experts model with 17B active parameters, featuring Qwen Coder - an autonomous coding agent for writing, debugging, and fixing code. Supports native context of 262K tokens, extensible to 1M tokens.\",\n   318→    \"author\": \"Alibaba Qwen Team\",\n   319→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   320→    \"url\": \"https://qwen-ai.com/\",\n   321→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   322→    \"topics\": [\n   323→      \"qwen\",\n   324→      \"qwen-coder\",\n   325→      \"moe\",\n   326→      \"coding-agents\",\n   327→      \"chinese-ai\",\n   328→      \"llm-release\"\n   329→    ],\n   330→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   331→  },\n   332→  {\n   333→    \"title\": \"GPT-5.3-Codex and OpenAI Frontier announced\",\n   334→    \"description\": \"OpenAI announced GPT-5.3-Codex, 25% faster than previous versions, setting new records on SWE-Bench Pro. Launched alongside OpenAI Frontier AI Agent platform for enterprise deployment, focusing on production-grade AI agent systems with improved reliability and memory mechanisms.\",\n   335→    \"author\": \"OpenAI\",\n   336→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   337→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/w/1856334665745420/\",\n   338→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   339→    \"topics\": [\n   340→      \"openai\",\n   341→      \"gpt-5.3-codex\",\n   342→      \"frontier\",\n   343→      \"enterprise\",\n   344→      \"ai-agents\",\n   345→      \"benchmarks\"\n   346→    ],\n   347→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   348→  },\n   349→  {\n   350→    \"title\": \"Claude Opus 4.6 and Agent Team functionality\",\n   351→    \"description\": \"Anthropic announced Claude Opus 4.6 with significantly improved programming capabilities, finding 500+ high-risk vulnerabilities in open-source libraries. Introduced 'Agent Team' functionality for parallel task coordination, enabling multiple AI agents to work together on complex problems.\",\n   352→    \"author\": \"Anthropic\",\n   353→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   354→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/w/1856334665745420/\",\n   355→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   356→    \"topics\": [\n   357→      \"anthropic\",\n   358→      \"claude-opus-4.6\",\n   359→      \"agent-team\",\n   360→      \"security\",\n   361→      \"parallel-coordination\",\n   362→      \"llm-release\"\n   363→    ],\n   364→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   365→  },\n   366→  {\n   367→    \"title\": \"SWE-Bench breakthrough: 70%+ success rate\",\n   368→    \"description\": \"AI coding agents improved from solving 33% of problems in August 2024 to over 70% by early 2026 on SWE-Bench. This dramatic improvement marks a tipping point in AI coding capabilities, with major implications for software development workflows.\",\n   369→    \"author\": \"Industry analysis\",\n   370→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   371→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/w/1857227001200651/\",\n   372→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   373→    \"topics\": [\n   374→      \"swe-bench\",\n   375→      \"benchmarks\",\n   376→      \"ai-coding\",\n   377→      \"progress-tracking\",\n   378→      \"industry-metrics\"\n   379→    ],\n   380→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n   381→  },\n   382→  {\n   383→    \"title\": \"2026: From explosive growth to delivery phase\",\n   384→    \"description\": \"Industry analysts identify 2026 as a pivotal transition year where AI moves from generating content to orchestrating workflows and completing actual tasks. The shift from 'explosive growth' to 'delivery phase' emphasizes practical implementation over hype.\",\n   385→    \"author\": \"Industry analysts\",\n   386→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n   387→    \"url\": \"https://m.toutiao.com/w/1857227001200651/\",\n   388→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-21\",\n   389→    \"topics\": [\n   390→      \"industry-trends\",\n   391→      \"ai-adoption\",\n   392→      \"workflow-automation\",\n   393→      \"delivery-phase\",\n   394→      \"paradigm-shift\"\n   395→    ],\n   396→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n   397→  }\n   398→]\n   399→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
      }
    ]
